{{Politics of Ukraine}}
'''All-Ukrainian Political Union Women for the Future''' ({{lang-uk|Всеукраїнське політичне об’єднання "Жінки за майбутнє"}}) is a political party in Ukraine registered on 30 March 2001. The party was created by Lyudmila Kuchma, a wife of the then serving [[President of Ukraine]] [[Leonid Kuchma]]. Among notable party candidates was [[Dmytro Firtash]].

At the [[legislative]] [[Ukrainian parliamentary election, 2002|elections of 30 March 2002]], the party won 2.1% of the popular vote and no seats;<ref name=SD/> although final poll results had predicted 5% till 6% of the total votes for the party.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/1898223.stm Ukraine's election frontrunners], [[BBC News]] (28 March 2002)</ref> At the [[legislative]] [[Ukrainian parliamentary election, 2006|elections of 26 March 2006]], the party was part of the [[Opposition Bloc "Ne Tak"]].<ref name=SD/> The party did not participate in the [[Ukrainian parliamentary election, 2007|2007 elections]].<ref name=SD>[http://sd.net.ua/2009/08/30/zhnki_za_majjbutn_vseukranske_poltichne_obdnannja.html Databases ASD: Political parties in Ukraine]</ref>

